contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:36.788 --> 01:38.321
(THUMPING ON DOCK)

01:48.300 --> 01:51.167
- (INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)
- (GAVEL BANGS)

01:59.824 --> 02:01.230
(DOOR CLOSES)

02:04.516 --> 02:06.716
If this is you trying to bum
another ride home,

02:06.718 --> 02:07.917
it has to stop.

02:07.919 --> 02:09.384
People are starting to talk.

02:10.655 --> 02:13.022
Dr. Bull, I need...

02:13.024 --> 02:14.357
I need a favor.

02:14.359 --> 02:16.559
Oh. Well, for you, Judge Abernathy,

02:16.561 --> 02:18.895
a woman who I greatly admire,
and in front of whom

02:18.897 --> 02:20.730
I'm trying a quarter of
a billion dollar case...

02:20.732 --> 02:24.419
This will, of course, have no
bearing on the matter before me.

02:25.587 --> 02:27.971
Name it. You need a five?

02:27.973 --> 02:30.006
A ten? In unmarked quarters?

02:30.008 --> 02:33.309
A friend, a colleague
in the DA's office,

02:33.311 --> 02:37.413
just caught a difficult
and high-profile case.

02:37.415 --> 02:38.982
I know it's short notice,

02:38.984 --> 02:40.883
but if there's any
help you can give him.

02:40.885 --> 02:43.219
Don't think twice. Consider it done.

02:45.590 --> 02:47.056
(BULL CLEARS THROAT)

02:47.058 --> 02:49.258
(WHISTLES SOFTLY)

02:52.897 --> 02:54.430
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

02:54.432 --> 02:56.632
(SIREN WAILS)

02:58.636 --> 03:00.670
- Dr. Bull?
- Yes.

03:00.672 --> 03:01.871
I'm guessing you're the ADA

03:01.873 --> 03:03.306
Judge Abernathy wanted me to meet.

03:03.308 --> 03:04.474
I am.

03:04.476 --> 03:05.742
Richmond.

03:05.744 --> 03:07.276
Richmond Abernathy.

03:07.278 --> 03:08.945
Aha.

03:08.947 --> 03:10.780
So... the son?

03:10.782 --> 03:13.051
Guilty as charged.

03:14.119 --> 03:15.918
What can I do for you?

03:15.920 --> 03:17.653
A Lennox University student

03:17.655 --> 03:19.789
was found floating in
the Hudson this morning.

03:19.791 --> 03:22.469
Name's Sam Wayland, 18 years old,

03:22.494 --> 03:24.093
pledging a fraternity.

03:24.095 --> 03:25.361
Gather you think there's a connection.

03:25.363 --> 03:26.496
How could I not?

03:26.498 --> 03:27.730
Made any arrests?

03:27.732 --> 03:29.276
That's why you're here.

03:30.769 --> 03:33.536
With all due respect
to you and your mother,

03:33.538 --> 03:35.672
this feels a little premature.

03:35.674 --> 03:37.307
I'm a trial consultant.

03:37.309 --> 03:38.994
I know.

03:39.537 --> 03:42.504
But mother claims you're also
an expert in human behavior.

03:42.647 --> 03:45.148
Said you're like a human lie detector.

03:45.150 --> 03:48.017
I'm not sure I believe
there is such a thing,

03:48.019 --> 03:50.420
but not like I have much of a choice.

03:50.422 --> 03:52.722
We've got to figure out who to charge.

03:53.409 --> 03:55.006
These are mostly rich white kids

03:55.008 --> 03:57.012
and they're lawyering up
even as we speak.

03:57.542 --> 03:59.765
I know I'm not gonna get any
of them near a polygraph.

04:00.665 --> 04:03.863
I think she was hoping
I could use you instead.

04:03.865 --> 04:07.770
Hazing? No. We don't
participate in hazing.

04:07.772 --> 04:09.706
What this was,

04:09.708 --> 04:12.241
was a-a “Welcome to Theta” celebration.

04:12.243 --> 04:13.643
It's something we look
forward to every year.

04:13.645 --> 04:15.044
See how his foot's pointed to the door?

04:15.046 --> 04:17.380
That's because he wants to escape

04:17.382 --> 04:18.615
because he's uncomfortable

04:18.617 --> 04:21.050
because... he's lying.

04:21.052 --> 04:23.353
LOGAN: Basically,
it's always the same thing.

04:23.355 --> 04:25.088
We have a few cocktails

04:25.090 --> 04:27.292
and then the pledges
go for a swim in the river.

04:27.321 --> 04:28.925
It's... essentially, it's like a

04:28.927 --> 04:30.297
“Welcome to Kappa Kappa Theta” thing.

04:30.299 --> 04:31.882
Hear the use of qualifiers?

04:31.884 --> 04:33.716
“Basically, essentially.”

04:33.718 --> 04:36.610
That's a fairly good indicator
someone's lying.

04:36.716 --> 04:39.513
I use qualifiers all the
time and I don't lie.

04:40.153 --> 04:42.153
(DOOR CLOSES)

04:42.155 --> 04:43.955
This is the victim's roommate.

04:43.957 --> 04:46.224
CARTER: We all got out of the water,

04:46.226 --> 04:48.259
walked back up to the frat house.

04:48.261 --> 04:50.061
Sam was right next to me.

04:50.063 --> 04:51.830
I mean, we were all a little loopy,

04:51.832 --> 04:54.069
but Sam was right there.

04:54.468 --> 04:57.783
We got in the room and went to bed.

04:57.785 --> 04:59.404
- Notice all the blinking?
- DETECTIVE: Did you undress?

04:59.406 --> 05:01.111
- DETECTIVE: Did he undress?
- Yeah.

05:01.113 --> 05:03.875
CARTER: I kicked my shoes off
and did a face-plant.

05:03.877 --> 05:05.876
Sam did pretty much the same thing.

05:05.878 --> 05:08.480
DETECTIVE: When did you first
realize he wasn't there?

05:08.482 --> 05:11.316
When you guys came to the door
this morning and woke us up.

05:11.318 --> 05:12.817
So you're telling me that Sam

05:12.819 --> 05:15.119
walked all the way back
to the dorm, got in bed,

05:15.121 --> 05:17.455
and then changed his mind,

05:17.457 --> 05:18.857
and went back to the river by himself?

05:18.859 --> 05:20.158
Why would he do that?

05:20.160 --> 05:21.659
CARTER: Maybe he forgot his cell phone?

05:22.013 --> 05:23.328
I have no idea.

05:23.330 --> 05:24.496
DETECTIVE: But that's your story.

05:24.498 --> 05:26.264
- Yes, sir.
- Yes, sir.

05:26.266 --> 05:27.198
Absolutely.

05:27.200 --> 05:28.399
- Yep.
- Yep.

05:28.401 --> 05:29.634
That's what happened.

05:29.636 --> 05:31.135
RICHMOND: <i>So, according to you,</i>

05:31.137 --> 05:32.337
they're all lying.

05:32.339 --> 05:35.573
Hey. I'm not selling anything.

05:35.575 --> 05:37.075
You asked what I thought.

05:37.077 --> 05:39.110
Take what you need and leave the rest.

05:40.106 --> 05:41.272
Anything else?

05:41.581 --> 05:43.014
Assistant District Attorney Abernathy.

05:43.016 --> 05:44.315
The victim's mother's

05:44.317 --> 05:45.884
still waiting in 102.

05:45.886 --> 05:47.418
She's having a pretty rough time.

05:47.420 --> 05:48.957
Can I give her an ETA?

05:49.422 --> 05:51.322
I honestly don't have
anything to tell her.

05:52.002 --> 05:53.712
Need some company?

05:55.936 --> 05:58.303
REBECCA WAYLAND:
You have nothing to tell me?

05:58.391 --> 06:01.325
Nothing beyond what the
coroner's determined.

06:01.401 --> 06:04.068
Which is, in and of
itself, very preliminary.

06:04.070 --> 06:06.057
Did he fall in?

06:07.374 --> 06:08.940
Was he pushed?

06:08.942 --> 06:12.710
Did... did he get a... a cramp,

06:12.712 --> 06:15.213
or did someone hold him underwater?

06:15.215 --> 06:17.235
What ever happened,

06:17.918 --> 06:19.877
was he frightened or just...

06:19.878 --> 06:20.910
surprised?

06:20.912 --> 06:22.679
I mean, was he alone,

06:22.681 --> 06:24.914
or were there other people?

06:24.916 --> 06:29.419
Was this deliberate
or was it an accident?

06:32.924 --> 06:36.572
Oh, for God's sake, tell me something!

06:36.574 --> 06:38.561
(SIGHS)

06:38.563 --> 06:42.065
I have a working theory.

06:43.335 --> 06:45.002
Sam was taking part in a hazing.

06:45.237 --> 06:46.870
There was a lot of drinking.

06:46.872 --> 06:48.738
Things got out of control.

06:48.740 --> 06:51.041
And the boys went swimming.

06:51.043 --> 06:53.209
And after Sam drowned,
for whatever reason,

06:53.939 --> 06:55.470
they decided not to call it in.

06:55.472 --> 06:57.364
And for the moment,
they have banded together.

06:57.366 --> 07:00.517
And they've all agreed on the same story

07:00.519 --> 07:02.919
about Sam going back to his room,

07:02.921 --> 07:04.954
and, according to them,

07:04.956 --> 07:08.358
returning to the river by himself.

07:08.360 --> 07:12.185
You're saying there were
other people there.

07:12.187 --> 07:14.297
We don't know that for sure.

07:14.299 --> 07:16.232
But if your theory's right,

07:16.234 --> 07:19.069
why wouldn't one of
those boys go and get help?

07:19.071 --> 07:22.300
Or call 911, or call the police?

07:24.177 --> 07:25.573
No. No.

07:25.598 --> 07:28.765
I... I don't want to believe that.

07:30.559 --> 07:32.582
It's like two deaths.

07:32.584 --> 07:36.152
It's not... human.

07:36.731 --> 07:38.588
Mrs. Wayland,

07:39.401 --> 07:41.624
people act differently in groups.

07:41.626 --> 07:44.194
They just... do.

07:44.196 --> 07:46.763
You add alcohol to the mix and
they're capable of doing things

07:46.765 --> 07:48.965
they would never do if they were alone.

07:50.078 --> 07:51.901
But...

07:51.903 --> 07:54.040
what about now?

07:54.806 --> 07:57.440
Why isn't someone stepping forward now?

07:57.442 --> 07:59.109
BULL: It's part of the dynamic.

07:59.111 --> 08:01.244
People commit to a certain
course of action,

08:01.246 --> 08:02.979
and they stick to it.

08:03.508 --> 08:05.081
The key is to undermine the alliance

08:05.083 --> 08:07.784
- they've made to each other,
- (CHAIR SCRAPES)

08:07.786 --> 08:10.098
and that is what we're gonna do.

08:11.022 --> 08:12.856
I promise you,

08:13.226 --> 08:15.091
before we're through here,

08:15.562 --> 08:19.028
you will know the truth.

08:19.030 --> 08:21.798
(SIREN WAILS NEARBY)

08:21.800 --> 08:23.433
You made a lot of promises in there,

08:23.435 --> 08:24.868
and now I have to keep them.

08:24.870 --> 08:26.169
And, honestly, I don't think I can.

08:26.171 --> 08:27.570
Well, I wouldn't have made them

08:27.572 --> 08:29.005
if I wasn't prepared to help you,

08:29.007 --> 08:30.373
assuming you want my help.

08:30.375 --> 08:31.841
Why don't you ask that victim's mother

08:31.843 --> 08:33.275
if she wants my help.

08:33.278 --> 08:34.677
It's not that I don't want your help.

08:35.498 --> 08:37.147
Look, you were my mother's idea.

08:37.149 --> 08:38.313
Yeah, and what does she know?

08:38.316 --> 08:39.816
She's only been doing it for 30 years.

08:39.818 --> 08:41.384
I don't have to explain myself to you.

08:41.385 --> 08:43.919
Well, then let me explain you to you.

08:43.922 --> 08:45.355
You think you're smarter
than everybody else.

08:45.357 --> 08:46.556
You think you're morally superior.

08:46.558 --> 08:49.692
And you think you got this
legal thing wired because

08:49.694 --> 08:51.528
you had the highest marks in your class

08:51.530 --> 08:54.664
or the best handwriting,
or I don't know.

08:54.666 --> 08:56.833
You've been assistant
district attorney for what?

08:56.835 --> 08:59.736
A minute? And you're
too stupid to realize

08:59.738 --> 09:01.871
that it costs you nothing to listen.

09:01.873 --> 09:03.740
You can hear my ideas
and still reject them

09:03.742 --> 09:05.654
without me being any the wiser,

09:05.700 --> 09:08.211
instead of letting me know
with your smug affect

09:08.213 --> 09:09.512
just how little you think of me.

09:09.514 --> 09:11.214
Oh, and one more thing.

09:11.534 --> 09:12.949
You got no people skills.

09:12.951 --> 09:14.884
That woman just lost her son,

09:14.886 --> 09:16.519
and what she needed to hear from you

09:16.521 --> 09:18.421
was that you were gonna
get her some answers,

09:18.423 --> 09:19.722
even if you didn't have any.

09:19.724 --> 09:21.057
But you're so arrogant,

09:21.059 --> 09:24.227
and you're working so hard
to be honest with her,

09:24.229 --> 09:27.263
that you didn't see what was
required there was a good lie.

09:27.265 --> 09:28.998
Although, I'd bet the house

09:29.000 --> 09:31.067
you think there's no such thing
as a good lie.

09:31.069 --> 09:33.837
Be sure and tell your mother
how amazing I was.

09:37.242 --> 09:39.742
Okay, Doctor, I'm all ears.

09:39.744 --> 09:42.178
These 15 kids are my only witnesses,

09:42.180 --> 09:43.580
and all their stories synced.

09:43.582 --> 09:45.181
So, obviously, someone sat them down.

09:45.183 --> 09:46.416
Obviously, someone rehearsed them.

09:46.418 --> 09:47.851
So what do you suggest I do?

09:47.853 --> 09:50.053
I'd put so much pressure
on those college boys

09:50.055 --> 09:52.288
they'd turn back into preschoolers.

09:52.290 --> 09:54.390
We need them to start
turning on each other.

09:54.392 --> 09:55.725
And how do I do that?

09:55.727 --> 09:57.093
Well, here's a crazy idea.

09:57.095 --> 09:58.461
Start filing charges.

09:58.463 --> 09:59.929
Against who?

09:59.931 --> 10:01.898
Against all of them, all 15.

10:01.900 --> 10:03.299
Charge them with manslaughter.

10:03.301 --> 10:04.667
Make those boys sweat.

10:04.669 --> 10:05.935
Make their parents sweat.

10:05.937 --> 10:07.504
Make them hire expensive lawyers,

10:07.506 --> 10:08.805
and make them sweat, too.

10:08.807 --> 10:11.374
You want me to charge 15 kids
with manslaughter?

10:11.376 --> 10:13.276
All due respect, that's insane.

10:13.278 --> 10:14.644
I knew you'd like it.

10:14.646 --> 10:16.246
There is no evidence.

10:16.248 --> 10:18.815
I won't be able to convict
one person, let alone 15.

10:18.817 --> 10:21.317
If we charge all of them,
someone will break

10:21.771 --> 10:23.620
and come forward looking for a deal.

10:23.622 --> 10:25.288
And that is how we find our guy.

10:25.900 --> 10:27.590
And if that doesn't happen?

10:27.592 --> 10:30.393
Then I'll be wrong and that
hasn't happened since 2005.

10:30.395 --> 10:31.694
It was a Wednesday.

10:31.696 --> 10:34.464
I said it was gonna rain,
it only drizzled.

10:34.466 --> 10:36.799
And by the way, I'm doing this
for the grieving mother.

10:36.801 --> 10:37.967
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

10:37.969 --> 10:39.502
Not for you.

10:44.276 --> 10:50.050
Synced & corrected by -robtor-
www.addic7ed.com

10:50.508 --> 10:52.562
Well, here's something
you don't see every day,

10:52.589 --> 10:53.888
15 Lennox University students,

10:53.890 --> 10:55.983
all of them members or pledges

10:56.030 --> 10:57.263
of Kappa Kappa Theta,

10:57.265 --> 10:58.598
doing the “perp walk”

10:58.600 --> 11:00.233
after they were all booked on the order

11:00.235 --> 11:02.935
of Assistant District Attorney
Richmond Abernathy.

11:02.937 --> 11:05.238
You orchestrated all this, didn't you?

11:06.252 --> 11:09.409
Called the press, worked out the timing?

11:09.411 --> 11:11.110
You can thank me later.

11:11.112 --> 11:14.072
- You hear that sound?
- What?

11:14.074 --> 11:15.648
It's the sound of your phone ringing

11:15.650 --> 11:17.650
with calls from frantic moms and dads

11:17.652 --> 11:19.886
who just saw their baby boys on TV

11:19.888 --> 11:22.355
and want to know how
they can cut a deal.

11:22.357 --> 11:25.224
(INDISTINCT POLICE RADIO CHATTER)

11:25.226 --> 11:28.528
CABLE: I was able to hack into
the fraternity security system.

11:28.530 --> 11:30.530
Now, this camera's at the back door.

11:30.532 --> 11:33.199
And I don't know who's who,
but I can tell

11:33.201 --> 11:37.637
that 16 kids left the fraternity
a little after 1:00 a.m.

11:37.639 --> 11:40.139
And it looks like only 15
came back a little after 4:00.

11:40.141 --> 11:42.675
BULL: Okay. What about the other doors?

11:42.677 --> 11:45.077
Are they all monitored? Could Sam have

11:45.079 --> 11:47.380
slipped in and then slipped
back out through a side door?

11:47.382 --> 11:49.182
'Cause that's what
the other side's gonna argue.

11:49.184 --> 11:51.217
Yeah, but didn't you say
the roommate told the cops

11:51.219 --> 11:52.485
that they all came in together,

11:52.487 --> 11:54.497
- went to bed together?
- Mm-hmm.

11:54.499 --> 11:56.255
He also said
he was extremely intoxicated,

11:56.257 --> 12:00.226
left himself plenty
of plausible deniability.

12:00.228 --> 12:01.494
Can we get somebody down

12:01.496 --> 12:02.929
to City Hall, Department of Records?

12:02.931 --> 12:05.631
Let's get a set of plans for that house,

12:05.633 --> 12:07.467
see every ingress and egress.

12:07.469 --> 12:08.768
Marissa?!

12:08.770 --> 12:12.205
Uh, I, uh, actually
don't think she's in yet.

12:12.590 --> 12:13.739
What are you talking about?

12:13.741 --> 12:16.075
It's Marissa. She's always in.

12:16.077 --> 12:17.777
I've worked with her for six years.

12:17.779 --> 12:19.512
She's never even had a cold.

12:20.478 --> 12:22.475
Should we call her?

12:22.978 --> 12:25.111
Should we call the police?

12:27.355 --> 12:28.754
She's fine, Dr. Bull.

12:28.756 --> 12:31.257
She's just running late.

12:32.443 --> 12:34.527
What does that mean?

12:34.988 --> 12:36.429
Do you know where she is?

12:36.431 --> 12:39.999
I know that she's fine, and
I know she'll be here soon.

12:40.001 --> 12:42.101
Okay.

12:42.103 --> 12:44.437
Apparently, I just work here.

12:45.039 --> 12:46.672
I'll be in my office.

12:52.247 --> 12:54.914
He had booze in his belly
and water in his lungs.

12:54.916 --> 12:56.148
Blood alcohol level?

12:56.150 --> 12:58.885
.43, enough to make a rhino tipsy.

12:58.887 --> 13:00.219
Didn't kill him, though.

13:00.221 --> 13:01.654
How's that?

13:01.656 --> 13:03.322
This boy died from asphyxiation.

13:03.324 --> 13:05.391
While he was in the water, he aspirated.

13:05.393 --> 13:07.727
Choked to death on his own vomit.

13:08.229 --> 13:10.796
Horrible, violent way to die.

13:17.005 --> 13:19.038
A death like that...

13:19.040 --> 13:20.673
would be noisy, right?

13:21.034 --> 13:22.408
Hard to ignore?

13:22.952 --> 13:24.143
If there were people around,

13:24.145 --> 13:26.045
I think it would be impossible
to ignore.

13:26.047 --> 13:27.780
<i>(KNOCKING ON DOOR)</i>

13:28.750 --> 13:31.417
Hey. Sorry to bother you.

13:31.419 --> 13:33.619
My name is Rex Bond.
I own Rex's Bail Bonds.

13:33.621 --> 13:35.715
Hi. Hey, Mr. Daniels?

13:36.424 --> 13:39.492
MAN: It's just totally crazy, you know?

13:39.494 --> 13:41.394
Rob Daniels. How can I help you?

13:41.396 --> 13:44.309
I'm guessing you're
an attorney. Huh? Huh?

13:44.311 --> 13:45.520
(LAUGHS)

13:45.522 --> 13:48.167
My name is Rex Bond.
I own Rex's Bail Bonds.

13:48.169 --> 13:50.929
I understand the kids are out
on their parents' recognizance,

13:50.931 --> 13:53.072
but if that should change,
I wanted to let them know

13:53.074 --> 13:55.374
that we are ready
and willing to be of help.

13:55.376 --> 13:57.977
I'm talking no money down,
excellent rates.

13:57.979 --> 14:00.279
If I could just come in
and talk to the boys

14:00.281 --> 14:01.781
and leave them my card?

14:01.783 --> 14:03.349
You're not coming in here.

14:03.351 --> 14:05.318
You're not talking to any of these boys.

14:05.320 --> 14:07.386
- I'm not?
- No, you're not.

14:07.388 --> 14:09.457
I'm sure you understand.

14:10.525 --> 14:13.059
These boys have been charged
with a homicide.

14:13.061 --> 14:15.995
They're not gonna talk to just
anybody who comes in the door.

14:15.997 --> 14:17.674
Okay.

14:18.232 --> 14:19.966
I get that.

14:19.968 --> 14:22.034
But I'm glad that
I've made your acquaintance.

14:22.036 --> 14:24.804
I'm always looking
for good attorneys I can refer

14:24.806 --> 14:26.349
my clients to.

14:28.676 --> 14:30.743
Here you go.

14:30.745 --> 14:32.612
- Don't lose that.
- All right.

14:32.614 --> 14:34.714
(CLICKS TONGUE, CHUCKLES)

14:34.716 --> 14:37.717
- (FLICKS BUSINESS CARD)
- Thank you.

14:37.719 --> 14:39.952
Oh. Hey.

14:39.954 --> 14:42.188
(LAUGHING): Hey. Full house.

14:44.283 --> 14:45.725
MARISSA: <i>Sorry.</i>

14:45.727 --> 14:47.026
Sorry. Sorry.

14:47.028 --> 14:49.195
I will be there in one minute.

14:49.197 --> 14:50.963
(SIGHS)

14:50.965 --> 14:52.264
You okay?

14:52.266 --> 14:53.933
Yeah. Of course.

14:53.935 --> 14:55.334
I'm fine. Late, but fine.

14:55.336 --> 14:57.403
Really? I'm concerned.

14:57.405 --> 14:58.971
This is so not like you.

14:58.973 --> 15:00.706
Anything you want to tell me?

15:00.708 --> 15:02.274
Oh, like what?

15:02.276 --> 15:04.343
Like, are you looking for another job?

15:04.345 --> 15:05.511
No.

15:05.513 --> 15:06.912
No.

15:06.914 --> 15:08.481
I'm not looking for another job.

15:09.684 --> 15:11.183
Doctor appointment?

15:11.185 --> 15:13.586
Yeah, okay, I did not have
a doctor's appointment.

15:13.588 --> 15:15.921
Nothing is wrong with me,
everything is fine.

15:15.923 --> 15:17.757
I am truly sorry for being late.

15:17.759 --> 15:20.226
So what kind of job are
you interviewing for?

15:20.228 --> 15:21.594
Okay, Bull...

15:21.596 --> 15:22.828
Huh?

15:22.830 --> 15:24.897
Look, we have been together

15:24.899 --> 15:27.733
for... ever.

15:27.735 --> 15:30.503
And I am very happy here, very happy.

15:30.505 --> 15:31.671
And I am very healthy.

15:31.673 --> 15:33.673
No worries there. No worries at all.

15:33.675 --> 15:37.243
I'm sorry if I caused you... concern.

15:38.337 --> 15:39.845
So, where were you?

15:39.847 --> 15:42.515
I was nowhere. It was nothing.

15:43.785 --> 15:45.985
I went out to dinner last night,

15:45.987 --> 15:48.988
and... one thing led to another,

15:48.990 --> 15:51.490
and I guess you could say I...

15:51.492 --> 15:55.561
ended up having
an irresponsible evening.

15:57.398 --> 15:59.031
I'm sorry.

15:59.033 --> 16:00.166
I think. Um, are...?

16:00.168 --> 16:01.500
Are we done?

16:01.502 --> 16:03.202
Mission accomplished.

16:05.406 --> 16:07.940
BENNY: Oh, what do you got there, Chunk?

16:07.942 --> 16:11.746
Oh. Wow. Those boys are lawyered up.

16:13.039 --> 16:14.413
I hate to be a buzzkill,

16:14.415 --> 16:17.616
but those boys just
might be telling the truth.

16:17.618 --> 16:20.419
(LAUGHS) Excuse me. I've been
doing this for a very long time,

16:20.421 --> 16:22.221
and they're telling everything
<i>but</i> the truth.

16:22.223 --> 16:23.556
I'm just saying.

16:23.558 --> 16:27.026
According to the coroner, Sam's
death was violent and loud.

16:27.512 --> 16:30.796
It's hard to imagine 15 guys
just standing around,

16:30.798 --> 16:32.164
- watching him die.
- Dr. Bull?

16:32.166 --> 16:33.999
You have a call from Assistant
District Attorney Abernathy.

16:34.001 --> 16:35.768
I put the call in your office.

16:35.770 --> 16:37.105
Thank you.

16:38.306 --> 16:39.405
What's the good news?

16:39.407 --> 16:40.639
RICHMOND: Dr. Bull,

16:40.641 --> 16:41.941
you promised me an eyewitness.

16:41.943 --> 16:43.576
Have you received any calls?

16:43.578 --> 16:44.710
No.

16:44.712 --> 16:45.845
Yeah. Nor have I.

16:45.847 --> 16:47.413
The trial starts tomorrow,

16:47.415 --> 16:49.381
and no one's looking to flip.

16:49.383 --> 16:50.916
There are no deals on the table.

16:50.918 --> 16:52.785
Well, let's not quit
before we get started.

16:52.787 --> 16:54.086
That's easy for you to say.

16:54.088 --> 16:56.422
This is all gonna land on me, Dr. Bull.

16:57.166 --> 16:59.558
Losing the one kid might have been bad,

16:59.560 --> 17:01.327
but losing the 15?

17:01.329 --> 17:03.429
I might as well start packing my desk.

17:03.431 --> 17:05.798
Well, I'll be sure
to convey your selfless concerns

17:05.800 --> 17:07.465
to the victim's next of kin.

17:07.468 --> 17:09.667
(CLICK, DIAL TONE)

17:10.505 --> 17:12.348
(SIGHS)

17:14.787 --> 17:16.739
Didn't think it'd actually get to this.

17:16.787 --> 17:18.916
- A trial with 15 defendants?
- Mm.

17:18.919 --> 17:22.660
I was sure somebody'd
break ranks, make a deal,

17:22.760 --> 17:24.660
tell us what actually
happened that night.

17:24.662 --> 17:26.328
So what are we looking for?

17:26.329 --> 17:27.666
Jury-wise, I mean.

17:27.669 --> 17:29.732
You ever heard of the threshold number?

17:29.734 --> 17:31.100
That would be a “no”"

17:31.102 --> 17:33.308
It's the number of people
who have to make a decision

17:33.310 --> 17:35.424
before you or I might make the same one.

17:35.425 --> 17:37.825
One person breaks
a store window, it's a robbery.

17:37.827 --> 17:40.395
Ten people break store windows,
it's a riot.

17:40.397 --> 17:41.896
The question is,

17:41.898 --> 17:44.132
how many people had to start
breaking store windows

17:44.134 --> 17:46.770
before the others
felt comfortable joining in?

17:46.772 --> 17:50.371
How many fraternity brothers
had to say they were...

17:50.373 --> 17:53.041
okay walking away from this kid drowning

17:53.514 --> 17:55.610
before everybody else
was willing to join in?

17:55.612 --> 17:57.545
Okay. I get that.

17:57.547 --> 18:00.114
But how does that help us figure
out who we want on the jury?

18:00.116 --> 18:02.383
(BASKETBALL DRIBBLING)

18:08.425 --> 18:09.780
What am I missing?

18:10.360 --> 18:13.294
That guy. He's our perfect juror.

18:13.296 --> 18:15.733
That guy? The guy throwing
the granny shots?

18:15.735 --> 18:18.466
- Why? 'Cause he looks ridiculous?
- Precisely.

18:18.468 --> 18:19.467
He doesn't care.

18:19.469 --> 18:21.236
As long as the shots are going in.

18:21.834 --> 18:24.072
You know, Wilt Chamberlain,
one of the greatest players

18:24.074 --> 18:26.007
- that ever lived...
- And a lousy foul shooter.

18:26.009 --> 18:27.909
One year, just for the hell of it,

18:27.911 --> 18:31.412
decides to shoot
all his free throws underhand.

18:31.414 --> 18:33.804
Even scored over 100 points one game.

18:34.584 --> 18:36.985
Never did it again, though.

18:36.987 --> 18:39.554
Power of peer pressure.

18:40.144 --> 18:41.823
JUDGE: <i>Be seated.</i>

18:49.966 --> 18:52.133
A little gift from me to you.

18:52.135 --> 18:53.568
What the hell are you doing?

18:53.570 --> 18:56.869
I'm helping you find
a high-threshold jury.

18:59.809 --> 19:02.410
Do any of you belong to, uh, any groups,

19:02.412 --> 19:05.847
clubs, organizations?

19:07.617 --> 19:09.884
I sing in my church choir

19:09.886 --> 19:12.787
and I'm part of my neighborhood watch.

19:14.650 --> 19:15.916
MARISSA: Oh, she is

19:15.918 --> 19:17.284
a joiner, Bull.

19:17.286 --> 19:18.986
Also, she belongs to the PTA,

19:18.988 --> 19:20.654
and she's on the board
of her community center.

19:20.656 --> 19:22.189
A pox on her house.

19:22.191 --> 19:23.690
Move to strike, Your Honor.

19:23.692 --> 19:25.592
And what about you, sir?

19:25.594 --> 19:27.194
Do you participate in any organizations?

19:27.196 --> 19:28.762
I belong to the Rotary.

19:28.764 --> 19:30.364
MARISSA: The president
of his local chapter

19:30.366 --> 19:32.399
three years in a row.

19:32.401 --> 19:34.601
Move to strike, Your Honor.

19:36.205 --> 19:38.338
Sir, it says here

19:38.340 --> 19:41.074
you're an officer on your co-op board.

19:41.539 --> 19:43.410
- What's your title?
- Treasurer.

19:43.412 --> 19:45.712
Bull's-eye. Talk about a thankless job.

19:45.714 --> 19:47.014
People must hate him.

19:47.016 --> 19:49.216
But he doesn't care,
which means we love him.

19:49.218 --> 19:51.107
Marissa, talk to me.

19:51.109 --> 19:52.519
What do you need, Dr. Bull?

19:52.521 --> 19:54.206
Marissa's not there?

19:54.208 --> 19:55.822
Um, she had...

19:55.824 --> 19:57.641
- an emergency.
- (LAUGHING)

19:57.643 --> 19:58.926
Can I help you?

19:58.928 --> 20:00.794
- What kind of emergency?
- JUROR: By the way,

20:00.796 --> 20:02.396
your pen is leaking.

20:02.398 --> 20:03.864
Oh. (CHUCKLES)

20:03.866 --> 20:05.332
You don't say.

20:05.334 --> 20:08.767
Never mind. I don't need her.

20:08.769 --> 20:11.672
This juror's acceptable
to the prosecution, Your Honor.

20:16.478 --> 20:17.911
That was a very expensive shirt.

20:17.913 --> 20:20.881
That was a very expensive pen.

20:21.750 --> 20:24.051
Anyone feel like tapas?

20:24.920 --> 20:26.375
Gentlemen.

20:26.855 --> 20:29.256
Mr. Assistant District Attorney?

20:29.795 --> 20:31.391
Sorry to interrupt
your lunch break, gentlemen,

20:31.393 --> 20:33.126
but I was hoping to get a word.

20:33.128 --> 20:34.428
What's on your mind, Counselor?

20:34.430 --> 20:36.730
Well, I know you're not
gonna like this, but, uh,

20:36.732 --> 20:39.299
I believe that
what we're looking at here

20:39.301 --> 20:42.202
is a tragic accident.
Nothing more, nothing less.

20:42.204 --> 20:45.672
But to compound the felony
by destroying 15 young lives...

20:45.674 --> 20:47.908
it makes no sense.

20:47.910 --> 20:49.643
There's no physical evidence,
you got no eyewitnesses.

20:49.645 --> 20:50.911
BULL: Wait a second.

20:50.913 --> 20:53.213
None of that changes the fact
that someone died

20:53.215 --> 20:54.648
during the commission of a crime.

20:54.650 --> 20:57.284
Excuse me, Jury Consultant.

20:58.153 --> 20:59.453
What crime?

20:59.455 --> 21:01.221
Contributing to the delinquency
of a minor.

21:01.223 --> 21:03.624
Providing alcohol
to someone who is underage.

21:03.626 --> 21:06.126
And by the way, I'm a trial scientist.

21:06.540 --> 21:08.262
What I do is, I tell lawyers...

21:08.264 --> 21:10.197
the ones who are smart enough
to listen...

21:10.802 --> 21:12.933
what to do so they can win their cases.

21:12.935 --> 21:14.868
And they pay me very well for it.

21:14.870 --> 21:17.738
I'm guessing you and I are not
destined to work together.

21:18.386 --> 21:20.340
These boys, including the victim,

21:20.342 --> 21:22.242
were doing what college kids
have been doing

21:22.244 --> 21:23.910
for 100 years... drinking.

21:23.912 --> 21:26.413
You really want to send them
to prison for that?

21:26.415 --> 21:28.782
An 18-year-old boy died, Counselor.

21:28.784 --> 21:30.150
And a mother lost her child.

21:30.152 --> 21:31.418
Absolutely.

21:31.420 --> 21:34.247
It's a tragedy, but it's
a tragedy born of an accident.

21:34.249 --> 21:37.057
No one set out to murder this poor boy.

21:37.059 --> 21:39.026
My clients weren't even present
when it happened.

21:39.028 --> 21:40.627
So they say.

21:40.908 --> 21:42.429
I tell you what.

21:43.869 --> 21:45.499
I'll let 14 of them walk.

21:45.501 --> 21:47.367
Mr. Assistant District Attorney.

21:47.369 --> 21:50.751
I will... under one condition.

21:51.307 --> 21:53.974
I want the person responsible.

21:54.547 --> 21:57.144
The one who said,
“Let's get these pledges drunk”"

21:57.633 --> 21:59.279
The one who said,
“Let's take them for a swim.”

21:59.281 --> 22:02.683
I want that person to come forward

22:02.685 --> 22:04.618
and accept responsibility.

22:05.057 --> 22:08.455
There's no such person,
Mr. Assistant District Attorney.

22:09.812 --> 22:11.558
Enjoy your lunch, gentlemen.

22:15.164 --> 22:16.697
BULL: <i>Well, this is a career first.</i>

22:17.319 --> 22:19.266
<i>We're about to start a trial,
and I have no case.</i>

22:19.268 --> 22:21.702
- We have a case.
- No, we don't.

22:22.158 --> 22:24.404
No. My idea didn't work.

22:24.785 --> 22:27.074
I was sure they'd crack
and somebody would come to us

22:27.076 --> 22:30.110
and tell us the truth, but... (SIGHS)

22:30.112 --> 22:33.347
they just offered to let us surrender.

22:38.420 --> 22:39.820
Look at that.

22:39.822 --> 22:41.388
Not one, “I'm sorry.”

22:41.390 --> 22:43.290
Not one, “He was my friend.”

22:43.292 --> 22:45.058
BENNY: They're all terrified,

22:45.060 --> 22:46.927
just not terrified enough
to break ranks.

22:46.929 --> 22:48.328
BULL: You know what?

22:48.330 --> 22:50.230
We're doing this backward.

22:50.232 --> 22:51.465
What are you talking about?

22:51.467 --> 22:53.767
I'm tired of waiting for them
to come to us.

22:53.769 --> 22:56.636
Let's pick one kid,
separate him from the pack,

22:56.638 --> 22:58.705
and dismiss the charges against him.

22:58.707 --> 23:00.107
What do you mean? Offer him immunity?

23:02.111 --> 23:04.811
Yeah. That's exactly what I mean.

23:04.813 --> 23:07.180
- We have to be smart about it, though.
- (WATER RUNNING)

23:07.182 --> 23:08.782
We have to pick the right guy.

23:08.784 --> 23:10.751
Not the guy we really think is guilty.

23:10.753 --> 23:12.586
We want to see him punished.

23:12.588 --> 23:15.222
We got to pick a guy we can squeeze,

23:15.224 --> 23:18.925
a guy we can put on the stand
and scare the crap out of.

23:18.927 --> 23:21.228
Make him understand,

23:21.230 --> 23:23.230
once we've immunized him,

23:23.232 --> 23:26.900
if he doesn't cooperate,
he'll be locked up for contempt.

23:26.902 --> 23:30.003
If he lies, he'll be
locked up for perjury.

23:32.207 --> 23:34.107
I know just the guy.

23:36.369 --> 23:39.575
All I'm trying to say is, if
you approach it mathematically,

23:39.626 --> 23:41.460
his roommate Carter
is the most vulnerable.

23:41.462 --> 23:42.961
I don't understand.

23:42.963 --> 23:44.863
What do you mean, “mathematically”?

23:44.865 --> 23:46.865
Well, other than lies of omission,

23:46.867 --> 23:48.600
the only lies everybody had tell

23:48.602 --> 23:50.502
were that Sam got out of the water

23:50.504 --> 23:53.238
and went back to the frat house
with them... two lies.

23:53.240 --> 23:54.940
Carter, on the other hand,

23:54.942 --> 23:57.042
had to go a lot further.
He had to say that he and Sam

23:57.044 --> 24:00.645
made it back to the room
together and they went to bed.

24:00.647 --> 24:02.848
And that therefore Sam must have snuck

24:02.850 --> 24:05.617
out of the house after
everybody was asleep,

24:05.619 --> 24:07.552
and died alone.

24:07.554 --> 24:09.287
Under a grant of immunity,
he must testify,

24:09.289 --> 24:11.790
and if he lies, he is subject
to ten years in prison.

24:11.792 --> 24:14.392
Remember, the point of all this
is to get him to tell us

24:14.394 --> 24:15.527
what really happened that night.

24:15.529 --> 24:17.529
You have got to use his testimony

24:17.531 --> 24:19.164
against him like a club,

24:19.166 --> 24:20.799
and beat him with it,

24:20.801 --> 24:23.445
until he tells us what we need to know.

24:25.614 --> 24:28.039
I know what I need to do.

24:29.785 --> 24:32.677
Well, if you know what to do,
then our job here is done.

24:41.054 --> 24:42.320
Marissa.

24:42.322 --> 24:43.716
Uh, did you call me?

24:44.717 --> 24:46.191
When do I get to meet him?

24:46.193 --> 24:47.559
Meet who?

24:47.561 --> 24:49.261
Mr. Irresponsible.

24:49.263 --> 24:50.929
Let's just see if it lasts the weekend

24:50.931 --> 24:52.564
before we plan the wedding.

24:52.566 --> 24:54.533
(CHUCKLES)

24:54.535 --> 24:56.868
You know how important you are to me.

24:57.229 --> 24:59.204
I think so.

24:59.206 --> 25:02.207
And you can call me anytime.

25:02.693 --> 25:04.809
Day or night with anything.

25:04.811 --> 25:06.244
That is sweet.

25:06.989 --> 25:08.113
I'm fine, Bull.

25:08.115 --> 25:10.549
In fact, I'm better than fine.

25:11.035 --> 25:12.584
I'm happy.

25:13.420 --> 25:15.520
I'm happy you're happy.

25:16.123 --> 25:17.255
Go get some sleep.

25:22.462 --> 25:24.162
RICHMOND: <i>You're here on
a grant of immunity.</i>

25:24.590 --> 25:26.398
Um, yes, sir.

25:26.400 --> 25:28.466
That means, so as long
as you tell the truth,

25:29.194 --> 25:32.337
anything you say here,
we can't use it against you.

25:32.890 --> 25:34.573
That's what my lawyer said.

25:35.476 --> 25:37.208
RICHMOND: You and Sam were roommates.

25:37.210 --> 25:38.559
Would you say you were friends?

25:38.599 --> 25:39.665
Well, uh,

25:39.667 --> 25:42.387
we just met six weeks ago,

25:42.389 --> 25:44.014
but, yes.

25:44.016 --> 25:45.704
W-We liked each other.

25:45.706 --> 25:46.839
RICHMOND: On this particular night,

25:46.841 --> 25:48.781
there was a pledge party.

25:49.656 --> 25:52.611
I think you told the detective
it was a celebration.

25:53.827 --> 25:56.348
Was there alcohol at the celebration?

25:56.789 --> 25:58.117
Yes.

25:58.119 --> 25:59.625
Did you drink?

26:01.168 --> 26:02.188
Yes.

26:02.190 --> 26:04.356
Even though, here in New York State,

26:04.358 --> 26:05.658
you're under the legal drinking age.

26:05.660 --> 26:06.826
DANIELS: Your Honor.

26:06.828 --> 26:08.294
We're prepared to stipulate

26:08.296 --> 26:09.862
that there was underage drinking

26:09.864 --> 26:11.630
at the celebration.

26:11.632 --> 26:13.165
So stipulated.

26:13.680 --> 26:15.401
Did Sam drink?

26:15.403 --> 26:17.236
Yes, I-I saw him drink.

26:17.238 --> 26:18.804
Any idea how much?

26:18.806 --> 26:21.340
CARTER: I, uh, wasn't keeping track.

26:21.342 --> 26:22.842
(RICHMOND CLEARS THROAT)

26:22.844 --> 26:27.112
Coroner says Sam's blood alcohol
level was .43.

26:27.114 --> 26:28.813
Just to put it in perspective,

26:28.815 --> 26:30.815
symptoms in a typical human being

26:30.817 --> 26:34.186
with a blood alcohol level
between .3 and .4

26:34.188 --> 26:36.355
are complete unconsciousness,

26:36.357 --> 26:39.892
depressed or absent reflexes,
and impairment

26:39.894 --> 26:41.727
of circulation and respiration.

26:41.729 --> 26:43.996
Not to put too fine a point on it,

26:43.998 --> 26:45.731
but death has been known to occur

26:45.733 --> 26:49.802
at a blood alcohol level
of .37 or higher.

26:49.804 --> 26:53.339
And fatality is almost certain
for nearly all individuals

26:53.341 --> 26:55.241
at .45 or higher.

26:55.243 --> 26:56.742
DANIELS: Objection, Your Honor.

26:57.819 --> 26:59.745
Is counsel gonna ask a question?

26:59.747 --> 27:02.848
Sustained. Ask a question,
Mr. Abernathy.

27:02.850 --> 27:04.717
Happy to, Your Honor.

27:04.719 --> 27:06.318
So based on these findings,

27:06.320 --> 27:09.622
knowing that your roommate... friend...

27:09.624 --> 27:12.491
was almost certainly at the
very edge of consciousness,

27:12.493 --> 27:14.593
perhaps even death's door,

27:14.595 --> 27:16.376
is it still your testimony

27:16.378 --> 27:18.343
that he got out of the water on his own,

27:18.345 --> 27:20.532
traveled three quarters of a mile back

27:20.534 --> 27:22.167
to the fraternity house in the dark,

27:22.169 --> 27:25.404
climbed stairs to the second
floor and went to bed?

27:27.671 --> 27:29.441
Yes, sir.

27:29.443 --> 27:31.677
That is my testimony.

27:31.679 --> 27:33.474
RICHMOND: To the room you shared.

27:33.476 --> 27:34.845
Right beside each other.

27:35.616 --> 27:37.182
Yes, sir.

27:37.184 --> 27:39.141
Did he get undressed?

27:39.987 --> 27:42.421
We were already in our underwear.

27:42.423 --> 27:44.056
Did he brush his teeth?

27:46.127 --> 27:48.961
- I-I don't honestly remember.
- RICHMOND: But you are swearing

27:48.963 --> 27:50.863
under oath that the two of you

27:50.865 --> 27:52.164
returned to your room that night

27:52.166 --> 27:53.999
safe and sound, and that anything

27:54.001 --> 27:55.601
that happened to him
happened after that.

27:56.116 --> 27:57.536
Yes, sir.

28:05.112 --> 28:09.148
Son, do you know the
punishment for perjury?

28:09.671 --> 28:11.215
It's ten years.

28:11.646 --> 28:14.180
Ten years in prison
for lying to the court.

28:14.622 --> 28:15.754
I'm not lying.

28:15.756 --> 28:17.856
That's ten years per each lie, actually.

28:17.858 --> 28:19.425
So you'll be, what,

28:19.427 --> 28:21.760
29 when you get out? Or 39 or 49.

28:21.762 --> 28:23.362
DANIELS: Objection, Your Honor.

28:23.364 --> 28:25.464
We understand the concept of lying.

28:25.466 --> 28:28.300
We understand ten years,
and we all know how to count.

28:28.302 --> 28:30.302
I'm not lying.

28:31.193 --> 28:32.671
RICHMOND: What if I told you

28:32.673 --> 28:35.240
that I have security video
that shows 16 of you

28:35.242 --> 28:37.543
leaving the house for the celebration,

28:37.545 --> 28:39.511
but only 15 of you coming back?

28:40.369 --> 28:42.314
Would you be inclined
to change your story?

28:48.656 --> 28:50.656
(EXHALES)

28:50.658 --> 28:52.881
All that drinking...

28:54.091 --> 28:56.176
He needed to use the bathroom.

28:56.464 --> 28:58.464
He went in the side door.

28:58.466 --> 29:00.055
It's closer.

29:01.181 --> 29:02.968
No camera there.

29:02.970 --> 29:04.737
Is that your sworn testimony?

29:05.060 --> 29:07.039
(SIGHS) It is.

29:11.345 --> 29:13.527
Nothing further at this moment,
Your Honor.

29:14.215 --> 29:16.882
DANIELS: Defense has no
questions for this witness,

29:16.884 --> 29:18.751
- Your Honor.
- JUDGE: If counsel

29:18.753 --> 29:20.152
for both sides could approach the bench.

29:20.154 --> 29:21.687
What's Marissa saying?

29:21.689 --> 29:23.355
We created a lot of doubt,

29:23.357 --> 29:25.724
but not a lot of certainty
and people don't convict people

29:25.726 --> 29:27.626
based solely on doubt.

29:28.375 --> 29:30.195
RICHMOND: The judge would like
to see us in her chambers.

29:30.197 --> 29:33.499
She's threatening to dismiss the case.

29:33.501 --> 29:35.567
(EXHALES): Ooh.

29:37.853 --> 29:40.166
I've got 14 defendants in my courtroom.

29:40.606 --> 29:43.540
14 defendants, 12 jurors,
20-some parents,

29:43.542 --> 29:45.842
enough lawyers to hold a convention.

29:45.844 --> 29:48.796
But not one name on the witness list

29:48.798 --> 29:51.048
that promises to provide an iota of fact

29:51.050 --> 29:52.983
that will lead us anywhere different

29:52.985 --> 29:54.943
from where we are right now.

29:54.945 --> 29:56.253
In my opinion, this has been

29:56.255 --> 29:58.221
a colossal waste of time and resources.

29:58.223 --> 30:01.168
But, Your Honor,
that boy was obviously lying.

30:01.170 --> 30:02.992
That's a supposition, Your Honor.

30:02.994 --> 30:03.894
JUDGE: One we have neither the time

30:03.896 --> 30:06.463
nor the authority to adjudicate.

30:06.913 --> 30:08.532
That would have been
for the jury to decide.

30:08.534 --> 30:09.800
Would have been?

30:09.802 --> 30:11.501
JUDGE: I'm going to
issue a directed verdict.

30:11.503 --> 30:13.770
Everyone innocent on all counts.

30:13.772 --> 30:15.272
Let the defendants,
the jurors, everyone,

30:15.274 --> 30:18.050
- go home.
- BULL: But there's one more witness.

30:18.052 --> 30:20.110
JUDGE: Excuse me?

30:20.112 --> 30:22.312
I'm asking a favor, Your Honor.

30:23.096 --> 30:26.049
Allow us one more witness,

30:26.051 --> 30:29.653
and I believe we can bring this
to some kind of just conclusion.

30:29.655 --> 30:31.488
And who is this mystery witness?

30:31.490 --> 30:33.490
The person for whom I took on this case.

30:34.024 --> 30:34.925
The victim's mother.

30:34.927 --> 30:36.193
DANIELS: Excuse me.

30:36.195 --> 30:38.295
She wasn't there when her son died.

30:38.297 --> 30:40.997
She's not a percipient witness.

30:42.134 --> 30:44.909
We're not here to provide
catharsis, Dr. Bull.

30:44.911 --> 30:46.737
We're here to find the truth
and I fail to see

30:46.739 --> 30:48.372
how this is going to get us there.

30:48.374 --> 30:51.174
That's why I called it a favor,
Your Honor.

30:51.176 --> 30:54.578
You promised me you would
get me the truth.

30:54.580 --> 30:56.380
That's what I'm trying to do.

30:58.650 --> 31:00.117
They don't want to hear from me.

31:00.119 --> 31:02.018
They already know
everything I'm gonna say.

31:02.020 --> 31:03.487
Don't be so sure.

31:03.489 --> 31:06.857
You remember what you said
to me the first time we met?

31:07.349 --> 31:10.961
I told you I believed there were
people present when Sam died.

31:10.963 --> 31:12.996
And you said just the thought of that

31:12.998 --> 31:14.631
was like a second death to you.

31:15.399 --> 31:17.467
The boys need to hear that.

31:17.469 --> 31:20.470
It just might shake
the truth out of them.

31:22.241 --> 31:24.574
(SIGHS)

31:24.576 --> 31:26.810
Okay.

31:29.448 --> 31:31.615
Tell me what to say.

31:32.249 --> 31:33.717
Uh, Sam was an only child.

31:33.719 --> 31:35.218
He had no father.

31:35.220 --> 31:39.222
He had no brothers, so, the idea

31:39.224 --> 31:41.291
of being in a fraternity...

31:41.293 --> 31:43.360
a house full of brothers and fathers...

31:43.362 --> 31:44.861
he was very excited.

31:44.863 --> 31:46.029
DANIELS: Objection.

31:46.869 --> 31:47.898
Relevance.

31:47.900 --> 31:50.350
Ask a question, Mr. Abernathy.

31:52.227 --> 31:53.370
The day you got the call

31:53.372 --> 31:55.639
informing you that they
had found Sam's body,

31:56.523 --> 31:57.874
what were your reactions?

31:57.876 --> 32:00.577
Again. Relevance.

32:01.653 --> 32:03.413
Overruled.

32:03.415 --> 32:04.881
Let the woman speak.

32:05.240 --> 32:09.085
Well, there were many things.

32:10.162 --> 32:12.255
First I thought it must be some mistake

32:12.789 --> 32:15.000
and then I realized it wasn't...

32:15.694 --> 32:17.419
that Sam was gone.

32:17.896 --> 32:20.839
Just... gone.

32:21.567 --> 32:24.267
And then I realized that no one

32:24.269 --> 32:27.404
could look me in the eye
and tell me what happened.

32:28.013 --> 32:31.141
That apparently, no one knew.

32:32.100 --> 32:33.643
And that...

32:33.852 --> 32:36.313
I was gonna have to live
the rest of my life

32:36.980 --> 32:39.783
knowing one day I had a child,
and then the next day I didn't,

32:39.785 --> 32:42.419
but I would never know why.

32:42.944 --> 32:44.488
And then?

32:44.896 --> 32:47.357
And then it-it started to seem like...

32:47.359 --> 32:49.159
maybe somebody did know.

32:49.161 --> 32:51.428
Like, maybe there actually

32:51.430 --> 32:53.930
had been people there.
Like, a lot of people.

32:54.706 --> 32:58.168
And so, I wondered who made the choices.

32:58.627 --> 33:00.237
I mean, did they all

33:00.239 --> 33:02.939
just say, “Let's...

33:02.941 --> 33:05.408
go and get the pledges drunk”?

33:05.410 --> 33:08.712
Did they all just decide, “Hey, let's

33:08.714 --> 33:10.447
throw him in the river,” even though

33:10.449 --> 33:12.315
they're so drunk
they can't see straight?

33:12.317 --> 33:14.267
And then I gue...

33:15.053 --> 33:18.555
I guess... when Sam drowned...

33:20.292 --> 33:24.528
...did they all... decide,

33:25.487 --> 33:29.466
“Let's just not... call anybody.

33:29.908 --> 33:33.436
“Let's... go home.

33:34.454 --> 33:36.673
Let's just get some sleep”?

33:36.675 --> 33:39.309
DANIELS: Objection, Your Honor.

33:39.311 --> 33:40.744
I don't mean any disrespect,

33:40.746 --> 33:42.679
but I would be derelict in my duties

33:42.681 --> 33:44.748
if I did not object
to all this testimony

33:44.750 --> 33:46.550
based on relevance.

33:48.093 --> 33:49.119
Sustained.

33:49.803 --> 33:51.179
You're right.

33:52.224 --> 33:55.525
The jury will please disregard
everything they just heard.

33:55.527 --> 33:59.396
Right. Just go ahead and unhear that.

33:59.398 --> 34:01.898
JUDGE: Let's take a one hour recess,

34:01.900 --> 34:03.867
and counsel and I will
meet in my chambers

34:03.869 --> 34:05.168
to determine next steps.

34:06.232 --> 34:07.370
(GAVEL BANGS)

34:09.507 --> 34:11.841
Earth to Marissa. Talk to me.

34:13.118 --> 34:16.012
Uh, well, the jurors were clearly moved.

34:16.014 --> 34:17.414
BULL: Enough to convict?

34:17.416 --> 34:18.748
Yeah, not quite.

34:18.750 --> 34:22.502
Eight are green, and four are still red.

34:22.853 --> 34:24.521
What's your next move?

34:24.523 --> 34:26.590
Well, I'm probably gonna
do what most great men do

34:26.592 --> 34:28.358
when confronted with
a situation like this.

34:28.360 --> 34:29.659
Yeah. What's that?

34:29.661 --> 34:31.565
- Lie.
- Excuse me?

34:31.568 --> 34:32.929
I'll tell you all about it tonight

34:32.931 --> 34:34.531
when I get back to the office.

34:34.533 --> 34:36.800
Oh, and do me a favor.
20 minutes from now,

34:36.802 --> 34:38.201
will you please text Benny?

34:38.203 --> 34:40.103
- Uh, text Benny what?
- BULL: Doesn't matter.

34:40.105 --> 34:41.670
Just text him.

34:41.672 --> 34:44.139
Come on. Let's find Richmond Abernathy

34:44.141 --> 34:47.476
and see if we can convince him
to tell a couple of good lies,

34:47.478 --> 34:49.713
or at the very least, let us tell them

34:49.715 --> 34:51.947
without him blowing our cover.

34:52.284 --> 34:54.417
<i>Our algorithm's never wrong.</i>

34:54.418 --> 34:58.521
Rebecca's testimony
turned every single juror.

34:58.523 --> 35:01.424
14 boys, 14 convictions.

35:01.583 --> 35:03.226
And you know Judge Hanlon.

35:03.962 --> 35:05.328
It's not gonna be picking up trash

35:05.330 --> 35:07.297
on the side of the road. Mm-mm.

35:07.299 --> 35:08.698
You're going to prison.

35:08.700 --> 35:11.901
Logan, jury wants to hear from you.

35:11.903 --> 35:13.603
This is nonsense.

35:13.605 --> 35:16.272
You can't get a conviction
based on a bunch of stares.

35:16.274 --> 35:19.442
You're really willing to take
all your friends down with you?

35:19.444 --> 35:21.411
(PHONE CHIMES TWICE)

35:21.413 --> 35:23.146
Oh. Sorry.

35:23.897 --> 35:24.981
Huh.

35:25.607 --> 35:27.017
It's one of the lawyers.

35:27.359 --> 35:29.419
Somebody wants to make a deal.

35:29.421 --> 35:31.154
Should I step outside and call him back?

35:31.156 --> 35:33.588
One of the other lawyers?
Someone on my team?

35:33.590 --> 35:34.658
(PHONE VIBRATING)

35:34.660 --> 35:35.925
Let me see the phone.

35:35.927 --> 35:37.427
- Not gonna show you my phone.
- Why?

35:37.429 --> 35:38.762
'Cause there's no such text? Come on.

35:38.764 --> 35:39.863
Let me see it, big shot!

35:39.865 --> 35:41.370
- Hey, get your hands off me!
- Gentlemen!

35:41.372 --> 35:42.624
Quiet!

35:45.251 --> 35:46.549
(PHONE BEEPS)

35:47.295 --> 35:49.205
I just got two voice mails from parents

35:49.207 --> 35:51.975
who are willing
to allow their sons to testify

35:51.977 --> 35:54.077
in exchange for immunity.

35:55.345 --> 35:56.691
With all due respect,

35:56.693 --> 35:58.615
Mr. Assistant District Attorney,
would it be possible

35:58.617 --> 36:00.583
for me to hear those voice mails?

36:00.850 --> 36:03.987
I'm an officer of the court
for the State of New York.

36:05.855 --> 36:07.941
Are you suggesting that I'm a liar?

36:09.109 --> 36:10.226
Fine.

36:10.694 --> 36:12.128
Go and make imaginary deals

36:12.130 --> 36:14.964
with imaginary lawyers
and imaginary parents.

36:15.323 --> 36:16.666
We're done here.

36:16.668 --> 36:19.202
Being pretty cavalier with your
client's future. You're going

36:19.204 --> 36:20.704
home to bed tonight.

36:20.706 --> 36:23.139
He and all of his friends
are gonna do 15 years.

36:23.141 --> 36:25.141
15 years? Really?

36:25.143 --> 36:26.543
That's the sentence for manslaughter.

36:26.545 --> 36:28.244
That's the maximum.
No one gets the maximum.

36:28.246 --> 36:29.512
BENNY: They do in Judge Hanlon's

36:29.514 --> 36:31.548
- courtroom.
- And that's before I indict you

36:31.550 --> 36:33.083
for obstruction of justice.

36:33.085 --> 36:34.651
That's good for another,
well, ten years.

36:34.653 --> 36:38.188
No. No, I'm-I'm not going
to prison for 25 years.

36:38.190 --> 36:39.756
Then let me help you.

36:39.758 --> 36:42.392
Agree to testify, and let that jury

36:42.394 --> 36:45.128
and that grieving mother know
what really happened that night.

36:46.187 --> 36:47.630
And then I will go to the judge,

36:47.632 --> 36:50.366
and I will use every bit
of influence I have

36:50.368 --> 36:51.968
to get her to go easy on you.

36:51.970 --> 36:54.337
You just said Judge Hanlon
doesn't go easy on anyone.

36:54.339 --> 36:56.840
This is a business of favors,

36:57.198 --> 36:59.576
and I've done a ton of 'em.

37:00.076 --> 37:02.245
I guess it's time to collect.

37:02.247 --> 37:03.913
What do you say?

37:04.549 --> 37:07.751
When I was a kid, my grandpa
would talk about World War II.

37:08.620 --> 37:11.421
But my dad and my older brothers...

37:12.589 --> 37:16.192
they'd talk about Hell Night,
about pledging,

37:17.218 --> 37:19.480
about how surviving that ordeal
made you a man,

37:19.482 --> 37:20.800
and introduced you to the people

37:20.802 --> 37:23.199
that would stay your friends
for the rest of your life.

37:26.728 --> 37:28.938
We all really liked Sam.

37:29.939 --> 37:32.242
That's why we asked him to be one of us.

37:32.901 --> 37:35.145
Nobody expected him to die.

37:35.737 --> 37:37.280
Who bought the alcohol?

37:37.282 --> 37:39.048
I did.

37:39.050 --> 37:41.651
Uh, the fraternity, but we used my I.D.

37:42.160 --> 37:43.920
And who ordered the defendants to drink?

37:44.245 --> 37:46.189
Me, but, I mean, we all did.

37:46.191 --> 37:48.191
It-It's kind of what you do.

37:48.917 --> 37:50.877
And who marched him down to the dock?

37:52.545 --> 37:54.197
That was me.

37:54.199 --> 37:56.199
I had the megaphone,

37:56.633 --> 37:59.469
and I was the one who pushed Sam
into the water.

38:01.096 --> 38:02.839
RICHMOND: And how long
did you keep them there?

38:03.723 --> 38:06.276
I don't know. Maybe an hour.

38:06.278 --> 38:08.845
Uh, we were drinking and shouting

38:08.847 --> 38:12.315
and having a great time, and then,

38:12.317 --> 38:15.018
Carter... he was treading water...

38:15.777 --> 38:19.114
started to say he couldn't
see Sam anymore, so...

38:20.990 --> 38:22.792
we started calling his name,

38:22.794 --> 38:26.462
uh, diving into the water
to try and find him, but...

38:26.464 --> 38:28.431
you couldn't see anything. It...

38:28.433 --> 38:29.732
MAN: <i>Sam!</i>

38:29.734 --> 38:31.734
- It was black...
<i>- (ECHOING SHOUTS)</i>

38:31.736 --> 38:34.504
...so we just kept calling his name.

38:34.506 --> 38:37.407
Sam!

38:37.409 --> 38:39.676
Sam! Sam! Sam!

38:43.114 --> 38:46.808
And then, it kind of got quiet.
(SNIFFLES)

38:47.085 --> 38:49.285
We stopped calling his name.

38:50.103 --> 38:51.721
I-I guess we just realized

38:51.723 --> 38:53.823
that he wasn't there.

38:54.440 --> 38:55.592
And then,

38:55.594 --> 38:59.028
I said, um... I said this thing.

39:01.700 --> 39:03.199
I said... (SNIFFLES)

39:03.201 --> 39:06.169
“Well, maybe he just went back
to the house.”

39:08.206 --> 39:10.440
(SNIFFLING)

39:10.442 --> 39:12.675
I don't know where it came from,

39:13.334 --> 39:15.078
and I wish I had never said it.

39:15.080 --> 39:16.412
(SNIFFLES)

39:16.963 --> 39:19.148
It was just kind of...

39:19.757 --> 39:22.352
You could tell that... (CLEARS THROAT)

39:22.354 --> 39:26.356
The second they heard it, it was
what everyone wanted to hear.

39:26.931 --> 39:27.991
(SNIFFLES)

39:27.993 --> 39:32.595
We were drunk and stupid, and we didn't

39:32.597 --> 39:34.964
even think to call the police.

39:37.525 --> 39:39.369
Nobody said a word on the walk home,

39:39.371 --> 39:42.138
but I think we all realized that
there was a really good chance

39:42.140 --> 39:45.041
that our lives were gonna be
very different now.

39:47.869 --> 39:49.479
And what happened
when you got back home,

39:49.481 --> 39:50.947
and he wasn't there?

39:51.289 --> 39:53.349
Didn't anyone suggest
calling the authorities?

39:53.666 --> 39:55.551
Everybody was really drunk

39:55.553 --> 39:56.961
and really scared.

39:59.505 --> 40:00.857
Everyone just...

40:01.216 --> 40:02.859
went to their rooms and
either passed out or prayed

40:02.861 --> 40:05.128
that he'd show up the next
morning, and when he didn't...

40:05.130 --> 40:06.729
(SNIFFLES)

40:06.731 --> 40:08.689
...we made a promise to each other

40:09.510 --> 40:11.901
that we would not talk
about what had happened.

40:11.903 --> 40:13.269
Not to our lawyers.

40:15.104 --> 40:16.706
(VOICE BREAKING):
Not even to our parents.

40:16.708 --> 40:17.974
(SNIFFLES)

40:17.976 --> 40:20.143
And whose idea was that?

40:21.736 --> 40:23.746
That was me.

40:26.284 --> 40:28.051
(BREATH QUIVERING)

40:28.053 --> 40:30.253
I'm truly sorry.

40:32.324 --> 40:35.258
(GALLERY MURMURING)

40:37.252 --> 40:39.095
JUDGE: You've been convicted
of manslaughter

40:39.097 --> 40:41.431
in a sad and senseless death.

40:41.923 --> 40:44.901
A young man full of life
and promise is gone.

40:45.343 --> 40:47.370
And you had the power to stop it.

40:47.929 --> 40:50.039
But instead, you chose to indulge

40:50.041 --> 40:52.208
and encourage yourself and others

40:52.210 --> 40:54.978
in reckless and wanton behavior.

40:55.353 --> 40:57.280
I'm taking into account that

40:57.282 --> 40:59.636
you admitted to your role
in the incident

40:59.638 --> 41:01.684
and took responsibility for the effect

41:01.686 --> 41:03.736
of your behavior on others.

41:04.320 --> 41:08.198
And I will note that Dr. Bull,
a member of the opposing team,

41:08.552 --> 41:13.262
has spoken up on your behalf,
which is a rare occurrence.

41:14.080 --> 41:16.599
I'm not one to reward bad behavior,

41:18.001 --> 41:21.004
but in this case,
I'm going to make an exception.

41:21.006 --> 41:24.841
I hereby sentence you to serve
two years in state prison.

41:24.843 --> 41:26.843
(GALLERY MURMURING)

41:26.845 --> 41:29.078
(HANDCUFFS TIGHTEN)

41:33.184 --> 41:35.351
Not so fast.

41:37.050 --> 41:38.988
Sit down, please.

41:41.526 --> 41:44.660
The rest of you bare a certain
degree of culpability, as well.

41:45.278 --> 41:47.030
I'm sentencing each of you

41:47.032 --> 41:50.700
to 500 hours of community service.

41:50.702 --> 41:53.736
(GALLERY MURMURING)

41:54.537 --> 41:56.639
She took your suggestion.

42:01.878 --> 42:03.346
Dr. Bull.

42:03.348 --> 42:05.081
(SIGHS)

42:05.083 --> 42:07.417
Thank you.

42:07.800 --> 42:09.452
You kept your promise.

42:09.454 --> 42:11.179
I had a lot of help.

42:16.194 --> 42:17.531
